SENATE BILL No. 246
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
criminal law and procedure.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 33-41-1-5 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
2 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 5. (a) If requested to do
3 so, an official reporter shall furnish to either party in a cause a
4 transcript of all or any part of the proceedings required by the reporter
5 to be taken or noted, including all documentary evidence.
6 (b) An official reporter shall furnish a typewritten or printed
7 transcript described in subsection (a) as soon after being requested to
8 do so as practicable.
9 (c) The reporter shall certify that the transcript contains all the
10 evidence given in the cause.
11 (d) The reporter may require payment for a transcript, or that the
12 payment be satisfactorily secured, before the reporter proceeds to do
13 the required work.
14 (e) In a criminal action (as defined by IC 35-32-4-1), the official
15 reporter shall comply with the requirements for redaction under
16 IC 35-32-4.
17 SECTION 2. IC 35-31.5-2-72.7 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
ES 246—LS 7110/DI 106

2
1 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
2 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 72.7. "Criminal action", for
3 purposes of IC 35-32-4, has the meaning set forth in IC 35-32-4-1.
4 SECTION 3. IC 35-32-4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
5 A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
6 1, 2026]:
7 Chapter 4. References to Child Victims and Witnesses
8 Sec. 1. (a) This chapter applies only to a criminal action.
9 (b) As used in this chapter, "criminal action" means:
10 (1) an action to prosecute a misdemeanor or a felony;
11 (2) a criminal appeal or a postconviction proceeding; or
12 (3) a document, such as a probable cause affidavit:
13 (A) prepared by a law enforcement officer; and
14 (B) submitted to a judicial officer;
15 as part of an investigation into the possible commission of a
16 misdemeanor or felony, even if the investigation does not
17 result in a prosecution.
18 Sec. 2. In any document filed or submitted in a criminal action,
19 the following information must be redacted:
20 (1) A reference to the name of a child victim or a child
21 witness.
22 (2) A reference to the name of a person whose name is not
23 required to be redacted under subdivision (1), if the reference
24 to the name could be used to identify a child whose name is
25 required to be redacted under subdivision (1).
26 (3) Addresses (mail or electronic mail), dates of birth, and
27 telephone numbers of natural persons who are witnesses or
28 victims.
29 Sec. 3. The name of a person whose name is required to be
30 redacted under this chapter must be replaced with a descriptive
31 anonymous designator, such as "Child Witness No. 1" or
32 "Passenger". Initials or references to familial relationships may
33 not be used.
34 Sec. 4. If a reference to an unredacted name or other
35 information is necessary for the resolution of the criminal action,
36 any document containing the unredacted name or information
37 shall be filed as a separate confidential document in accordance
38 with Rule 5 of the Indiana Rules on Access to Court Records.
39 SECTION 4. IC 35-33-7-2, AS AMENDED BY P.L.131-2025,
40 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
41 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 2. (a) As used in this section, "affiant" means the
42 person who submits the facts upon which an arrest has been made:
ES 246—LS 7110/DI 106

3
1 (1) in a probable cause affidavit; or
2 (2) to a judicial officer orally, under oath.
3 (b) At or before the initial hearing of a person arrested without a
4 warrant for a crime, the facts upon which the arrest was made shall be
5 submitted to the judicial officer, ex parte, in a probable cause affidavit.
6 The affidavit must be prepared and filed in accordance with section 8
7 of this chapter. In lieu of the affidavit or in addition to it, the facts may
8 be submitted orally under oath to the judicial officer. If facts upon
9 which the arrest was made are submitted orally, the proceeding shall be
10 recorded by a court reporter, and, upon request of any party in the case
11 or upon order of the court, the record of the proceeding shall be
12 transcribed.
13 (c) In addition to the facts described in subsection (b), the affiant
14 shall disclose any known personal, financial, or familial relationship
15 with:
16 (1) any party to the investigation; or
17 (2) any other person involved in the offense described in the
18 affidavit;
19 if the relationship could reasonably be perceived to affect the affiant's
20 objectivity or impartiality.
21 (d) If the judicial officer determines that there is probable cause to
22 believe that any crime was committed and that the arrested person
23 committed it, the judicial officer shall order that the arrested person be
24 held to answer in the proper court. If the facts submitted do not
25 establish probable cause or if the prosecuting attorney informs the
26 judicial officer on the record that no charge will be filed against the
27 arrested person, the judicial officer shall order that the arrested person
28 be released immediately.
29 SECTION 5. IC 35-33-7-8 IS REPEALED [EFFECTIVE JULY 1,
30 2026]. Sec. 8. A probable cause affidavit must be redacted as follows:
31 (1) References to the name of a child witness or victim in a case
32 involving a sex offense allegedly committed against a child must
33 be replaced with a descriptive anonymous designator, such as
34 "Witness No. 1" or "Passenger". The use of initials and references
35 to familial relationships should be avoided.
36 (2) References to the name of a person whose name is not
37 required to be redacted under subdivision (1) must be redacted if
38 the reference to the name could be used to identify a child whose
39 name is required to be redacted under subdivision (1). The name
40 shall be redacted in the manner described in subdivision (1).
41 (3) Addresses (mail or electronic mail), dates of birth, and
42 telephone numbers of natural persons who are witnesses or
